LEISHMANIASIS, VISCERAL - CHINA (FUJIAN, HUBEI EX XINJIANG)
******************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[The original posting erroneously mispelled Xinjiang; and erroneously listed Xinjiang as in Eastern China. Xinjiang is in Western China, Fujian is on the Eastern Coast of China. The below posting has been modified to reflect these changes. - Mod.MPP]

[1] Fujian
[2] Hubei ex Xinjiang

******
[1] Fujian
Date: Fri 13 Apr 2007
From: Dan Silver <dgsilver@yahoo.com >
Source: Southeast Express [trans. by submitter from Chinese, edited]
<http://www.dnkb.com.cn/news/20070406/001046.html>


It was learned yesterday [5 Apr 2007] that Xiamen No. 1 Hospital
recently confirmed a case of extremely rare visceral leishmaniasis.
Xiamen Municipality [in southeastern Fujian province] has no prior
reports of this type of illness. This may be the 1st case in China
this year. On 19 Mar 2007, the patient was admitted to Xiamen No. 1
Hospital. The 30-year-old Anhuinese patient had had a fever above 40
deg C (104 deg F), accompanied by chills, for more than a month
before hospitalization at No. 1 Hospital. After 11 days of
hospitalization, the patient's fever continued, rising high twice a
day. Upon examination it was found that the patient's blood cell
count was extremely low, and the patient had significant hepatosplenomegaly.

On 26 Mar 2007, large quantities of _Leishmania donovani_ were found
in the bone marrow smears, [leading to] the final diagnosis of
visceral leishmaniasis. The patient was treated with sodium
stibogluconate injections.

--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The municipality of Xiamen in Fujian province can be located on the
map of China available at
<http://encarta.msn.com/map_701510630/Fujian.html>. - Mod.EP]


******
[2] Hubei ex Xinjiang
Date: Thu 12 Apr 2007
From: Dan Silver <dgsilver@yahoo.com

Source: Wuhan Evening News [trans. from Chinese by submitter, edited]
<http://www.hb.chinanews.com.cn/news/2007/2007-04-10/79845.html>


A case of visceral leishmaniasis was diagnosed in a young, returnee
labourer, who had returned from working in Xinjiang. Leishmaniasis is
spread through the bite of the sandfly. The patient was transferred
from a rural hospital to Wuhan Union Hospital and because he was
diagnosed with visceral leishmaniasis, he was then transferred to a
specialized infectious disease hospital.

Experts at Wuhan disease control agencies say that since 1949,
monitoring has shown that sandflies do not breed in Wuhan, so
visceral leishmaniasis cannot originate locally and cannot be
transmitted in Wuhan.

An official with Wuhan Disease Control Center's Infectious Disease
Prevention and Treatment Unit says that anyone traveling for work or
tourism can take the following precautions against visceral
leishmaniasis caused by bites from sandflies:

- Use of mosquito repellent, mosquito coils, and fumigation by
burning dry artemesia to expel sandflies;
- avoid sleep outdoors;
- ask for screen windows and screen doors;
- in hill zones with visceral leishmaniasis, insecticide sprays can
be used during sandfly season (May-September).

In recent years, visceral leishmaniasis has appeared mainly in Gansu,
Sichuan, Shaanxi, Shanxi, Xinjiang, Inner Mongolia, and other places.

--
